CAPE TOWN - The body of a 13-year-old boy has been recovered at Hout Bay Beach after the teen went missing in the surf on Sunday. NSRI Hout Bay station commander Geoff Stephens said at about 2:35pm, duty crew were activated following reports of a drowning in progress at Hout Bay Beach. NSRI sea rescue crafts were launched along with NSRI Hout Bay rescue swimmers. Lifeguards, EMS rescue, a Police Dive Unit and Hout Bay Community Crime Prevention among others responded to the scene. “An extensive search commenced for a 13-year-old missing in the surf. “The local teenager had been swimming with a friend when he got into difficulty and disappeared under water,” Stephens said. A search included rescue swimmers conducting sweeping line free dive search efforts and lifeguards using Malibu rescue boards while three sea rescue craft searched the surf zone. “During a search the teenager was located and recovered from shallow surf by NSRI rescue swimmers and Police divers.” The teen was declared dead on the scene and his body taken into the care of Police and Government Health Forensic Pathology Services. Stephens conveyed condolences to the family. Meanwhile, the search is continuing for a Mandalay teenager who was swept away in rip currents at Sunset Beach in Melkbosstrand on Saturday. Melkbosstrand's National Sea Rescue Institute spokesperson, Terence Lawson, NSRI said the teenager was one of four youth who got into difficulty in the surf. Three of them were rescued by bystanders including a Mauritian couple. Cape Times